Name: ACL
Summary: A container for Access List Control commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

SubCommands.Name: ACL|CAT
SubCommands.Summary: Lists the ACL categories, or the commands inside a category.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(1) since the categories and commands are a fixed set.

SubCommands.Name: ACL|DELUSER
SubCommands.Summary: Deletes ACL users, and terminates their connections.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(1) amortized time considering the typical user.

SubCommands.Name: ACL|GENPASS
SubCommands.Summary: Generates a pseudorandom, secure password that can be used to identify ACL users.

SubCommands.Name: ACL|GETUSER
SubCommands.Summary: Lists the ACL rules of a user.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of password, command and pattern rules that the user has.

SubCommands.Name: ACL|LIST
SubCommands.Summary: Dumps the effective rules in ACL file format.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of configured users.

SubCommands.Name: ACL|LOAD
SubCommands.Summary: Reloads the rules from the configured ACL file.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of configured users.

SubCommands.Name: ACL|SAVE
SubCommands.Summary: Saves the effective ACL rules in the configured ACL file.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of configured users.

SubCommands.Name: ACL|SETUSER
SubCommands.Summary: Creates and modifies an ACL user and its rules.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of rules provided.

SubCommands.Name: ACL|USERS
SubCommands.Summary: Lists all ACL users.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N). Where N is the number of configured users.

SubCommands.Name: ACL|WHOAMI
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the authenticated username of the current connection.

Name: APPEND
Summary: Appends a string to the value of a key. Creates the key if it doesn't exist.
Complexity: O(1). The amortized time complexity is O(1) assuming the appended value is small and the already present value is of any size, since the dynamic string library used by Redis will double the free space available on every reallocation.

Name: ASKING
Summary: Signals that a cluster client is following an -ASK redirect.

Name: ASYNC
Summary: Start, stop or issue a barrier command for a series of async operations.

Name: AUTH
Summary: Authenticates the connection.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of passwords defined for the user

Name: BGSAVE
Summary: Asynchronously saves the database(s) to disk.

Name: BITCOUNT
Summary: Counts the number of set bits (population counting) in a string.
Complexity: O(N)

Name: BITFIELD
Summary: Performs arbitrary bitfield integer operations on strings.
Complexity: O(1) for each subcommand specified

Name: BITFIELD_RO
Summary: Performs arbitrary read-only bitfield integer operations on strings.
Complexity: O(1) for each subcommand specified

Name: BITOP
Summary: Performs bitwise operations on multiple strings, and stores the result.
Complexity: O(N)

Name: BITPOS
Summary: Finds the first set (1) or clear (0) bit in a string.
Complexity: O(N)

Name: BLMOVE
Summary: Pops an element from a list, pushes it to another list and returns it. Blocks until an element is available otherwise. Deletes the list if the last element was moved.

Name: BLMPOP
Summary: Pops the first element from one of multiple lists. Blocks until an element is available otherwise. Deletes the list if the last element was popped.
Complexity: O(N+M) where N is the number of provided keys and M is the number of elements returned.

Name: BLPOP
Summary: Removes and returns the first element in a list. Blocks until an element is available otherwise. Deletes the list if the last element was popped.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of provided keys.

Name: BRPOP
Summary: Removes and returns the last element in a list. Blocks until an element is available otherwise. Deletes the list if the last element was popped.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of provided keys.

Name: BRPOPLPUSH
Summary: Pops an element from a list, pushes it to another list and returns it. Block until an element is available otherwise. Deletes the list if the last element was popped.

Name: BZMPOP
Summary: Removes and returns a member by score from one or more sorted sets. Blocks until a member is available otherwise. Deletes the sorted set if the last element was popped.
Complexity: O(K) + O(M*log(N)) where K is the number of provided keys, N being the number of elements in the sorted set, and M being the number of elements popped.

Name: BZPOPMAX
Summary: Removes and returns the member with the highest score from one or more sorted sets. Blocks until a member available otherwise.  Deletes the sorted set if the last element was popped.
Complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.

Name: BZPOPMIN
Summary: Removes and returns the member with the lowest score from one or more sorted sets. Blocks until a member is available otherwise. Deletes the sorted set if the last element was popped.
Complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.

Name: CLIENT
Summary: A container for client connection commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

SubCommands.Name: CLIENT|GETNAME
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the name of the connection.

SubCommands.Name: CLIENT|ID
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the unique client ID of the connection.

SubCommands.Name: CLIENT|INFO
SubCommands.Summary: Returns information about the connection.

SubCommands.Name: CLIENT|KILL
SubCommands.Summary: Terminates open connections.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of client connections

SubCommands.Name: CLIENT|LIST
SubCommands.Summary: Lists open connections.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of client connections

SubCommands.Name: CLIENT|SETINFO
SubCommands.Summary: Sets information specific to the client or connection.

SubCommands.Name: CLIENT|SETNAME
SubCommands.Summary: Sets the connection name.

SubCommands.Name: CLIENT|UNBLOCK
SubCommands.Summary: Unblocks a client blocked by a blocking command from a different connection.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(log N) where N is the number of client connections

Name: CLUSTER
Summary: A container for Redis Cluster internal commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|ADDSLOTS
SubCommands.Summary: Assigns new hash slots to a node.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of hash slot arguments

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|ADDSLOTSRANGE
SubCommands.Summary: Assigns new hash slot ranges to a node.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of the slots between the start slot and end slot arguments.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|BUMPEPOCH
SubCommands.Summary: Advances the cluster config epoch.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|COUNTKEYSINSLOT
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the number of keys in a hash slot.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|DELSLOTS
SubCommands.Summary: Sets hash slots as unbound for a node.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of hash slot arguments

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|DELSLOTSRANGE
SubCommands.Summary: Sets hash slot ranges as unbound for a node.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of the slots between the start slot and end slot arguments.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|FAILOVER
SubCommands.Summary: Forces a replica to perform a manual failover of its master.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|FLUSHALL
SubCommands.Summary: Sent by primary to replica to force to FLUSH its database

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|FORGET
SubCommands.Summary: Removes a node from the nodes table.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|GETKEYSINSLOT
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the key names in a hash slot.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of requested keys

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|HELP
SubCommands.Summary: Returns helpful text about the different subcommands.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|INFO
SubCommands.Summary: Returns information about the state of a node.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|KEYSLOT
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the hash slot for a key.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of bytes in the key

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|MEET
SubCommands.Summary: Forces a node to handshake with another node.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|MYID
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the ID of a node.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|NODES
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the cluster configuration for a node.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Cluster nodes

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|PUBLISH
SubCommands.Summary: Processes a forwarded published message from any node in the cluster

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|REPLICAS
SubCommands.Summary: Lists the replica nodes of a master node.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of replicas.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|REPLICATE
SubCommands.Summary: Configure a node as replica of a master node.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|RESET
SubCommands.Summary: Resets a node.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of known nodes. The command may execute a FLUSHALL as a side effect.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|SET-CONFIG-EPOCH
SubCommands.Summary: Sets the configuration epoch for a new node.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|SETSLOT
SubCommands.Summary: Binds a hash slot to a node.

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|SHARDS
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the mapping of cluster slots to shards.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of cluster nodes

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|SLOTS
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the mapping of cluster slots to nodes.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Cluster nodes

SubCommands.Name: CLUSTER|SPUBLISH
SubCommands.Summary: Processes a forwarded published message from a node in the same shard

Name: COMMAND
Summary: Returns detailed information about all commands.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of Redis commands

SubCommands.Name: COMMAND|COUNT
SubCommands.Summary: Returns a count of commands.

SubCommands.Name: COMMAND|DOCS
SubCommands.Summary: Returns documentary information about one, multiple or all commands.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of commands to look up

SubCommands.Name: COMMAND|GETKEYS
SubCommands.Summary: Extracts the key names from an arbitrary command.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of arguments to the command

SubCommands.Name: COMMAND|GETKEYSANDFLAGS
SubCommands.Summary: Extracts the key names and access flags for an arbitrary command.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of arguments to the command

SubCommands.Name: COMMAND|INFO
SubCommands.Summary: Returns information about one, multiple or all commands.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of commands to look up

Name: COMMITAOF
Summary: Commit to append-only file.

Name: CONFIG
Summary: A container for server configuration commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

SubCommands.Name: CONFIG|GET
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the effective values of configuration parameters.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) when N is the number of configuration parameters provided

SubCommands.Name: CONFIG|REWRITE
SubCommands.Summary: Persists the effective configuration to file.

SubCommands.Name: CONFIG|SET
SubCommands.Summary: Sets configuration parameters in-flight.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) when N is the number of configuration parameters provided

Name: COSCAN
Summary: Iterates over members of a collection object.
Complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection.

Name: DBSIZE
Summary: Returns the number of keys in the database.

Name: DEBUG
Summary: A container for debugging commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

Name: DECR
Summary: Decrements the integer value of a key by one. Uses 0 as initial value if the key doesn't exist.

Name: DECRBY
Summary: Decrements a number from the integer value of a key. Uses 0 as initial value if the key doesn't exist.

Name: DEL
Summary: Deletes one or more keys.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys that will be removed. When a key to remove holds a value other than a string, the individual complexity for this key is O(M) where M is the number of elements in the list, set, sorted set or hash. Removing a single key that holds a string value is O(1).

Name: DELIFGREATER
Summary: Deletes a key only if the provided Etag is strictly greater than the existing Etag for the key.

Name: DISCARD
Summary: Discards a transaction.
Complexity: O(N), when N is the number of queued commands

Name: DUMP
Summary: Returns a serialized representation of the value stored at a key.
Complexity: O(1) to access the key and additional O(N*M) to serialize it, where N is the number of Redis objects composing the value and M their average size. For small string values the time complexity is thus O(1)+O(1*M) where M is small, so simply O(1).

Name: ECHO
Summary: Returns the given string.

Name: EVAL
Summary: Executes a server-side Lua script.
Complexity: Depends on the script that is executed.

Name: EVALSHA
Summary: Executes a server-side Lua script by SHA1 digest.
Complexity: Depends on the script that is executed.

Name: EXEC
Summary: Executes all commands in a transaction.
Complexity: Depends on commands in the transaction

Name: EXISTS
Summary: Determines whether one or more keys exist.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to check.

Name: EXPDELSCAN
Summary: Scans mutable records to delete expired ones.
Complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration. N is the number of records in memory.

Name: EXPIRE
Summary: Sets the expiration time of a key in seconds.

Name: EXPIREAT
Summary: Sets the expiration time of a key to a Unix timestamp.

Name: EXPIRETIME
Summary: Returns the expiration time of a key as a Unix timestamp.

Name: FAILOVER
Summary: Starts a coordinated failover from a server to one of its replicas.

Name: FLUSHALL
Summary: Removes all keys from all databases.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of keys in all databases

Name: FLUSHDB
Summary: Remove all keys from the current database.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys in the selected database

Name: FORCEGC
Summary: Forces garbage collection.

Name: GEOADD
Summary: Adds one or more members to a geospatial index. The key is created if it doesn't exist.
Complexity: O(log(N)) for each item added, where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

Name: GEODIST
Summary: Returns the distance between two members of a geospatial index.

Name: GEOHASH
Summary: Returns members from a geospatial index as geohash strings.
Complexity: O(1) for each member requested.

Name: GEOPOS
Summary: Returns the longitude and latitude of members from a geospatial index.
Complexity: O(1) for each member requested.

Name: GEORADIUS
Summary: Queries a geospatial index for members within a distance from a coordinate, optionally stores the result.
Complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements inside the bounding box of the circular area delimited by center and radius and M is the number of items inside the index.

Name: GEORADIUS_RO
Summary: Returns members from a geospatial index that are within a distance from a coordinate.
Complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements inside the bounding box of the circular area delimited by center and radius and M is the number of items inside the index.

Name: GEORADIUSBYMEMBER
Summary: Queries a geospatial index for members within a distance from a member, optionally stores the result.
Complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements inside the bounding box of the circular area delimited by center and radius and M is the number of items inside the index.

Name: GEORADIUSBYMEMBER_RO
Summary: Returns members from a geospatial index that are within a distance from a member.
Complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements inside the bounding box of the circular area delimited by center and radius and M is the number of items inside the index.

Name: GEOSEARCH
Summary: Queries a geospatial index for members inside an area of a box or a circle.
Complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements in the grid-aligned bounding box area around the shape provided as the filter and M is the number of items inside the shape

Name: GEOSEARCHSTORE
Summary: Queries a geospatial index for members inside an area of a box or a circle, optionally stores the result.
Complexity: O(N+log(M)) where N is the number of elements in the grid-aligned bounding box area around the shape provided as the filter and M is the number of items inside the shape

Name: GET
Summary: Returns the string value of a key.

Name: GETBIT
Summary: Returns a bit value by offset.

Name: GETDEL
Summary: Returns the string value of a key after deleting the key.

Name: GETEX
Summary: Returns the string value of a key after setting its expiration time.

Name: GETIFNOTMATCH
Summary: Gets the ETag and value if the key's current etag does not match the given etag.

Name: GETRANGE
Summary: Returns a substring of the string stored at a key.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the length of the returned string. The complexity is ultimately determined by the returned length, but because creating a substring from an existing string is very cheap, it can be considered O(1) for small strings.

Name: GETSET
Summary: Returns the previous string value of a key after setting it to a new value.

Name: GETWITHETAG
Summary: Gets the ETag and value for the key

Name: HCOLLECT
Summary: Manually trigger deletion of expired fields from memory

Name: HDEL
Summary: Deletes one or more fields and their values from a hash. Deletes the hash if no fields remain.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields to be removed.

Name: HELLO
Summary: Handshakes with the Redis server.

Name: HEXISTS
Summary: Determines whether a field exists in a hash.

Name: HEXPIRE
Summary: Set expiry for hash field using relative time to expire (seconds)
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified fields

Name: HEXPIREAT
Summary: Set expiry for hash field using an absolute Unix timestamp (seconds)
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified fields

Name: HEXPIRETIME
Summary: Returns the expiration time of a hash field as a Unix timestamp, in seconds.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified fields

Name: HGET
Summary: Returns the value of a field in a hash.

Name: HGETALL
Summary: Returns all fields and values in a hash.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the size of the hash.

Name: HINCRBY
Summary: Increments the integer value of a field in a hash by a number. Uses 0 as initial value if the field doesn't exist.

Name: HINCRBYFLOAT
Summary: Increments the floating point value of a field by a number. Uses 0 as initial value if the field doesn't exist.

Name: HKEYS
Summary: Returns all fields in a hash.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the size of the hash.

Name: HLEN
Summary: Returns the number of fields in a hash.

Name: HMGET
Summary: Returns the values of all fields in a hash.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields being requested.

Name: HMSET
Summary: Sets the values of multiple fields.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields being set.

Name: HPERSIST
Summary: Removes the expiration time for each specified field
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified fields

Name: HPEXPIRE
Summary: Set expiry for hash field using relative time to expire (milliseconds)
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified fields

Name: HPEXPIREAT
Summary: Set expiry for hash field using an absolute Unix timestamp (milliseconds)
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified fields

Name: HPEXPIRETIME
Summary: Returns the expiration time of a hash field as a Unix timestamp, in msec.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified fields

Name: HPTTL
Summary: Returns the TTL in milliseconds of a hash field.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified fields

Name: HRANDFIELD
Summary: Returns one or more random fields from a hash.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of fields returned

Name: HSCAN
Summary: Iterates over fields and values of a hash.
Complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection.

Name: HSET
Summary: Creates or modifies the value of a field in a hash.
Complexity: O(1) for each field/value pair added, so O(N) to add N field/value pairs when the command is called with multiple field/value pairs.

Name: HSETNX
Summary: Sets the value of a field in a hash only when the field doesn't exist.

Name: HSTRLEN
Summary: Returns the length of the value of a field.

Name: HTTL
Summary: Returns the TTL in seconds of a hash field.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified fields

Name: HVALS
Summary: Returns all values in a hash.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the size of the hash.

Name: INCR
Summary: Increments the integer value of a key by one. Uses 0 as initial value if the key doesn't exist.

Name: INCRBY
Summary: Increments the integer value of a key by a number. Uses 0 as initial value if the key doesn't exist.

Name: INCRBYFLOAT
Summary: Increment the floating point value of a key by a number. Uses 0 as initial value if the key doesn't exist.

Name: INFO
Summary: Returns information and statistics about the server.

Name: KEYS
Summary: Returns all key names that match a pattern.
Complexity: O(N) with N being the number of keys in the database, under the assumption that the key names in the database and the given pattern have limited length.

Name: LASTSAVE
Summary: Returns the Unix timestamp of the last successful save to disk.

Name: LATENCY
Summary: A container for latency diagnostics commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

SubCommands.Name: LATENCY|HELP
SubCommands.Summary: Returns helpful text about the different subcommands.

SubCommands.Name: LATENCY|HISTOGRAM
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the cumulative distribution of latencies of a subset or all commands.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of commands with latency information being retrieved.

SubCommands.Name: LATENCY|RESET
SubCommands.Summary: Resets the latency data for one or more events.

Name: LCS
Summary: Finds the longest common substring.
Complexity: O(N*M) where N and M are the lengths of s1 and s2, respectively

Name: LINDEX
Summary: Returns an element from a list by its index.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements to traverse to get to the element at index. This makes asking for the first or the last element of the list O(1).

Name: LINSERT
Summary: Inserts an element before or after another element in a list.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements to traverse before seeing the value pivot. This means that inserting somewhere on the left end on the list (head) can be considered O(1) and inserting somewhere on the right end (tail) is O(N).

Name: LLEN
Summary: Returns the length of a list.

Name: LMOVE
Summary: Returns an element after popping it from one list and pushing it to another. Deletes the list if the last element was moved.

Name: LMPOP
Summary: Returns multiple elements from a list after removing them. Deletes the list if the last element was popped.
Complexity: O(N+M) where N is the number of provided keys and M is the number of elements returned.

Name: LPOP
Summary: Returns the first elements in a list after removing it. Deletes the list if the last element was popped.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements returned

Name: LPOS
Summary: Returns the index of matching elements in a list.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements in the list, for the average case. When searching for elements near the head or the tail of the list, or when the MAXLEN option is provided, the command may run in constant time.

Name: LPUSH
Summary: Prepends one or more elements to a list. Creates the key if it doesn't exist.
Complexity: O(1) for each element added, so O(N) to add N elements when the command is called with multiple arguments.

Name: LPUSHX
Summary: Prepends one or more elements to a list only when the list exists.
Complexity: O(1) for each element added, so O(N) to add N elements when the command is called with multiple arguments.

Name: LRANGE
Summary: Returns a range of elements from a list.
Complexity: O(S+N) where S is the distance of start offset from HEAD for small lists, from nearest end (HEAD or TAIL) for large lists; and N is the number of elements in the specified range.

Name: LREM
Summary: Removes elements from a list. Deletes the list if the last element was removed.
Complexity: O(N+M) where N is the length of the list and M is the number of elements removed.

Name: LSET
Summary: Sets the value of an element in a list by its index.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the length of the list. Setting either the first or the last element of the list is O(1).

Name: LTRIM
Summary: Removes elements from both ends a list. Deletes the list if all elements were trimmed.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements to be removed by the operation.

Name: MEMORY
Summary: A container for memory diagnostics commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

SubCommands.Name: MEMORY|USAGE
SubCommands.Summary: Estimates the memory usage of a key.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of samples.

Name: MGET
Summary: Atomically returns the string values of one or more keys.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to retrieve.

Name: MIGRATE
Summary: Atomically transfers a key from one Redis instance to another.
Complexity: This command actually executes a DUMP+DEL in the source instance, and a RESTORE in the target instance. See the pages of these commands for time complexity. Also an O(N) data transfer between the two instances is performed.

Name: MODULE
Summary: A container for module commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

SubCommands.Name: MODULE|LOADCS
SubCommands.Summary: Load a C# module in Garnet.

Name: MONITOR
Summary: Listens for all requests received by the server in real-time.

Name: MSET
Summary: Atomically creates or modifies the string values of one or more keys.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to set.

Name: MSETNX
Summary: Atomically modifies the string values of one or more keys only when all keys don't exist.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of keys to set.

Name: MULTI
Summary: Starts a transaction.

Name: PERSIST
Summary: Removes the expiration time of a key.

Name: PEXPIRE
Summary: Sets the expiration time of a key in milliseconds.

Name: PEXPIREAT
Summary: Sets the expiration time of a key to a Unix milliseconds timestamp.

Name: PEXPIRETIME
Summary: Returns the expiration time of a key as a Unix milliseconds timestamp.

Name: PFADD
Summary: Adds elements to a HyperLogLog key. Creates the key if it doesn't exist.
Complexity: O(1) to add every element.

Name: PFCOUNT
Summary: Returns the approximated cardinality of the set(s) observed by the HyperLogLog key(s).
Complexity: O(1) with a very small average constant time when called with a single key. O(N) with N being the number of keys, and much bigger constant times, when called with multiple keys.

Name: PFMERGE
Summary: Merges one or more HyperLogLog values into a single key.
Complexity: O(N) to merge N HyperLogLogs, but with high constant times.

Name: PING
Summary: Returns the server's liveliness response.

Name: PSETEX
Summary: Sets both string value and expiration time in milliseconds of a key. The key is created if it doesn't exist.

Name: PSUBSCRIBE
Summary: Listens for messages published to channels that match one or more patterns.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of patterns to subscribe to.

Name: PTTL
Summary: Returns the expiration time in milliseconds of a key.

Name: PUBLISH
Summary: Posts a message to a channel.
Complexity: O(N+M) where N is the number of clients subscribed to the receiving channel and M is the total number of subscribed patterns (by any client).

Name: PUBSUB
Summary: A container for Pub/Sub commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

SubCommands.Name: PUBSUB|CHANNELS
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the active channels.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of active channels, and assuming constant time pattern matching (relatively short channels and patterns)

SubCommands.Name: PUBSUB|NUMPAT
SubCommands.Summary: Returns a count of unique pattern subscriptions.

SubCommands.Name: PUBSUB|NUMSUB
SubCommands.Summary: Returns a count of subscribers to channels.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) for the NUMSUB subcommand, where N is the number of requested channels

Name: PUNSUBSCRIBE
Summary: Stops listening to messages published to channels that match one or more patterns.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of patterns to unsubscribe.

Name: PURGEBP
Summary: Purge cluster buffer pool for manager type.

Name: QUIT
Summary: Closes the connection.

Name: READONLY
Summary: Enables read-only queries for a connection to a Redis Cluster replica node.

Name: READWRITE
Summary: Enables read-write queries for a connection to a Reids Cluster replica node.

Name: REGISTERCS
Summary: Registers custom C# commands in Garnet.

Arguments.Name: NAME
Arguments.Summary: Name of the command to register

Arguments.Name: NUMPARAMS
Arguments.Summary: Numer of parameters of the command to register

Arguments.Name: CLASSNAME
Arguments.Summary: Name of class defining the command to register

Arguments.Name: EXPTICKS
Arguments.Summary: Expiry of the command to register (in ticks)

Arguments.Name: OBJCMDNAME
Arguments.Summary: The object command name, if applicable

Arguments.Name: INFO
Arguments.Summary: Path to JSON-serialized command info for registered commands

Arguments.Name: DOCS
Arguments.Summary: Path to JSON-serialized command docs for registered commands

Arguments.Name: SRC
Arguments.Summary: Source paths containing classes defining command to register

Name: RENAME
Summary: Renames a key and overwrites the destination.

Name: RENAMENX
Summary: Renames a key and overwrites the destination if the newkey does not exist.

Name: REPLICAOF
Summary: Configures a server as replica of another, or promotes it to a master.

Name: RESTORE
Summary: Creates a key from the serialized representation of a value.
Complexity: O(1) to create the new key and additional O(N*M) to reconstruct the serialized value, where N is the number of Redis objects composing the value and M their average size. For small string values the time complexity is thus O(1)+O(1*M) where M is small, so simply O(1). However for sorted set values the complexity is O(N*M*log(N)) because inserting values into sorted sets is O(log(N)).

Name: ROLE
Summary: Returns the replication role.

Name: RPOP
Summary: Returns and removes the last elements of a list. Deletes the list if the last element was popped.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements returned

Name: RPOPLPUSH
Summary: Returns the last element of a list after removing and pushing it to another list. Deletes the list if the last element was popped.

Name: RPUSH
Summary: Appends one or more elements to a list. Creates the key if it doesn't exist.
Complexity: O(1) for each element added, so O(N) to add N elements when the command is called with multiple arguments.

Name: RPUSHX
Summary: Appends an element to a list only when the list exists.
Complexity: O(1) for each element added, so O(N) to add N elements when the command is called with multiple arguments.

Name: RUNTXP
Summary: Run registered transaction in Garnet.

Name: SADD
Summary: Adds one or more members to a set. Creates the key if it doesn't exist.
Complexity: O(1) for each element added, so O(N) to add N elements when the command is called with multiple arguments.

Name: SAVE
Summary: Synchronously saves the database(s) to disk.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of keys in all databases

Name: SCAN
Summary: Iterates over the key names in the database.
Complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection.

Name: SCARD
Summary: Returns the number of members in a set.

Name: SCRIPT
Summary: A container for Lua scripts management commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

SubCommands.Name: SCRIPT|EXISTS
SubCommands.Summary: Determines whether server-side Lua scripts exist in the script cache.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) with N being the number of scripts to check (so checking a single script is an O(1) operation).

SubCommands.Name: SCRIPT|FLUSH
SubCommands.Summary: Removes all server-side Lua scripts from the script cache.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) with N being the number of scripts in cache

SubCommands.Name: SCRIPT|LOAD
SubCommands.Summary: Loads a server-side Lua script to the script cache.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) with N being the length in bytes of the script body.

Name: SDIFF
Summary: Returns the difference of multiple sets.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

Name: SDIFFSTORE
Summary: Stores the difference of multiple sets in a key.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

Name: SECONDARYOF
Summary: Configures a server as secondary of another, or promotes it to a primary.

Name: SELECT
Summary: Changes the selected database.

Name: SET
Summary: Sets the string value of a key, ignoring its type. The key is created if it doesn't exist.

Name: SETBIT
Summary: Sets or clears the bit at offset of the string value. Creates the key if it doesn't exist.

Name: SETEX
Summary: Sets the string value and expiration time of a key. Creates the key if it doesn't exist.

Name: SETIFGREATER
Summary: Sets a key value pair with the given etag only if (1) the etag given in the request is greater than the already existing etag ; or (2) there was no existing value; or (3) the existing value was not associated with any etag and the sent etag was greater than 0.

Name: SETIFMATCH
Summary: Sets a key value pair with the given etag only if (1) the etag given in the request matches the already existing etag ; or (2) there was no existing value; or (3) the existing value was not associated with any etag and the sent etag was 0.

Name: SETNX
Summary: Set the string value of a key only when the key doesn't exist.

Name: SETRANGE
Summary: Overwrites a part of a string value with another by an offset. Creates the key if it doesn't exist.
Complexity: O(1), not counting the time taken to copy the new string in place. Usually, this string is very small so the amortized complexity is O(1). Otherwise, complexity is O(M) with M being the length of the value argument.

Name: SINTER
Summary: Returns the intersect of multiple sets.
Complexity: O(N*M) worst case where N is the cardinality of the smallest set and M is the number of sets.

Name: SINTERCARD
Summary: Returns the number of members of the intersect of multiple sets.
Complexity: O(N*M) worst case where N is the cardinality of the smallest set and M is the number of sets.

Name: SINTERSTORE
Summary: Stores the intersect of multiple sets in a key.
Complexity: O(N*M) worst case where N is the cardinality of the smallest set and M is the number of sets.

Name: SISMEMBER
Summary: Determines whether a member belongs to a set.

Name: SLAVEOF
Summary: Sets a Redis server as a replica of another, or promotes it to being a master.

Name: SLOWLOG
Summary: A container for slow log commands.
Complexity: Depends on subcommand.

SubCommands.Name: SLOWLOG|GET
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the slow log's entries.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of entries returned

SubCommands.Name: SLOWLOG|HELP
SubCommands.Summary: Show helpful text about the different subcommands

SubCommands.Name: SLOWLOG|LEN
SubCommands.Summary: Returns the number of entries in the slow log.

SubCommands.Name: SLOWLOG|RESET
SubCommands.Summary: Clears all entries from the slow log.
SubCommands.Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of entries in the slowlog

Name: SMEMBERS
Summary: Returns all members of a set.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the set cardinality.

Name: SMISMEMBER
Summary: Determines whether multiple members belong to a set.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of elements being checked for membership

Name: SMOVE
Summary: Moves a member from one set to another.

Name: SPOP
Summary: Returns one or more random members from a set after removing them. Deletes the set if the last member was popped.
Complexity: Without the count argument O(1), otherwise O(N) where N is the value of the passed count.

Name: SPUBLISH
Summary: Post a message to a shard channel
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of clients subscribed to the receiving shard channel.

Name: SRANDMEMBER
Summary: Get one or multiple random members from a set
Complexity: Without the count argument O(1), otherwise O(N) where N is the absolute value of the passed count.

Name: SREM
Summary: Removes one or more members from a set. Deletes the set if the last member was removed.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of members to be removed.

Name: SSCAN
Summary: Iterates over members of a set.
Complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection.

Name: SSUBSCRIBE
Summary: Listens for messages published to shard channels.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of shard channels to subscribe to.

Name: STRLEN
Summary: Returns the length of a string value.

Name: SUBSCRIBE
Summary: Listens for messages published to channels.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of channels to subscribe to.

Name: SUBSTR
Summary: Returns a substring from a string value.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the length of the returned string. The complexity is ultimately determined by the returned length, but because creating a substring from an existing string is very cheap, it can be considered O(1) for small strings.

Name: SUNION
Summary: Returns the union of multiple sets.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

Name: SUNIONSTORE
Summary: Stores the union of multiple sets in a key.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of elements in all given sets.

Name: SWAPDB
Summary: Swaps two Redis databases.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the count of clients watching or blocking on keys from both databases.

Name: TIME
Summary: Returns the server time.

Name: TTL
Summary: Returns the expiration time in seconds of a key.

Name: TYPE
Summary: Determines the type of value stored at a key.

Name: UNLINK
Summary: Asynchronously deletes one or more keys.
Complexity: O(1) for each key removed regardless of its size. Then the command does O(N) work in a different thread in order to reclaim memory, where N is the number of allocations the deleted objects where composed of.

Name: UNSUBSCRIBE
Summary: Stops listening to messages posted to channels.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of channels to unsubscribe.

Name: UNWATCH
Summary: Forgets about watched keys of a transaction.

Name: VADD
Summary: Add a new element into the vector set.
Complexity: O(log(N))

Name: VCARD
Summary: Return the number of elements in a vector set.

Name: VDIM
Summary: Return the number of dimensions in a vector set.

Name: VEMB
Summary: Return the approximate vector associated with an element in a vector set.

Name: VGETATTR
Summary: Return the JSON attributes associated with the element in the vector set.

Name: VISMEMBER
Summary: Determines whether a member belongs to vector set.

Name: VLINKS
Summary: Return the neighbors of an element in a vector set.

Name: VRANDMEMBER
Summary: Return some number of random elements from a vector set.

Name: VREM
Summary: Remove an element from a vector set.
Complexity: O(log(N))

Name: VSETATTR
Summary: Store attributes alongside a member of a vector set.

Name: VSIM
Summary: Return elements similar to a given vector or existing element of a vector set.
Complexity: O(log(N))

Name: WATCH
Summary: Monitors changes to keys to determine the execution of a transaction.
Complexity: O(1) for every key.

Name: WATCHMS
Summary: Monitors changes to keys in main store to determine the execution of a transaction.
Complexity: O(1) for every key.

Name: WATCHOS
Summary: Monitors changes to keys in object store to determine the execution of a transaction.
Complexity: O(1) for every key.

Name: ZADD
Summary: Adds one or more members to a sorted set, or updates their scores. Creates the key if it doesn't exist.
Complexity: O(log(N)) for each item added, where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

Name: ZCARD
Summary: Returns the number of members in a sorted set.

Name: ZCOLLECT
Summary: Manually trigger deletion of expired members from memory for SortedSet

Name: ZCOUNT
Summary: Returns the count of members in a sorted set that have scores within a range.
Complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.

Name: ZDIFF
Summary: Returns the difference between multiple sorted sets.
Complexity: O(L + (N-K)log(N)) worst case where L is the total number of elements in all the sets, N is the size of the first set, and K is the size of the result set.

Name: ZDIFFSTORE
Summary: Stores the difference of multiple sorted sets in a key.
Complexity: O(L + (N-K)log(N)) worst case where L is the total number of elements in all the sets, N is the size of the first set, and K is the size of the result set.

Name: ZEXPIRE
Summary: Set expiry for sorted set member using relative time to expire (seconds)
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified members

Name: ZEXPIREAT
Summary: Set expiry for sorted set member using an absolute Unix timestamp (seconds)
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified members

Name: ZEXPIRETIME
Summary: Returns the expiration time of a sorted set member as a Unix timestamp, in seconds.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified members

Name: ZINCRBY
Summary: Increments the score of a member in a sorted set.
Complexity: O(log(N)) where N is the number of elements in the sorted set.

Name: ZINTER
Summary: Returns the intersect of multiple sorted sets.
Complexity: O(N*K)+O(M*log(M)) worst case with N being the smallest input sorted set, K being the number of input sorted sets and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.

Name: ZINTERCARD
Summary: Returns the number of members of the intersect of multiple sorted sets.
Complexity: O(N*K) worst case with N being the smallest input sorted set, K being the number of input sorted sets.

Name: ZINTERSTORE
Summary: Stores the intersect of multiple sorted sets in a key.
Complexity: O(N*K)+O(M*log(M)) worst case with N being the smallest input sorted set, K being the number of input sorted sets and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.

Name: ZLEXCOUNT
Summary: Returns the number of members in a sorted set within a lexicographical range.
Complexity: O(log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set.

Name: ZMPOP
Summary: Returns the highest- or lowest-scoring members from one or more sorted sets after removing them. Deletes the sorted set if the last member was popped.
Complexity: O(K) + O(M*log(N)) where K is the number of provided keys, N being the number of elements in the sorted set, and M being the number of elements popped.

Name: ZMSCORE
Summary: Returns the score of one or more members in a sorted set.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of members being requested.

Name: ZPERSIST
Summary: Removes the expiration time for each specified sorted set member
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified members

Name: ZPEXPIRE
Summary: Set expiry for sorted set member using relative time to expire (milliseconds)
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified members

Name: ZPEXPIREAT
Summary: Set expiry for sorted set member using an absolute Unix timestamp (milliseconds)
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified members

Name: ZPEXPIRETIME
Summary: Returns the expiration time of a sorted set member as a Unix timestamp, in msec.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified members

Name: ZPOPMAX
Summary: Returns the highest-scoring members from a sorted set after removing them. Deletes the sorted set if the last member was popped.
Complexity: O(log(N)*M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set, and M being the number of elements popped.

Name: ZPOPMIN
Summary: Returns the lowest-scoring members from a sorted set after removing them. Deletes the sorted set if the last member was popped.
Complexity: O(log(N)*M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set, and M being the number of elements popped.

Name: ZPTTL
Summary: Returns the TTL in milliseconds of a sorted set member.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified members

Name: ZRANDMEMBER
Summary: Returns one or more random members from a sorted set.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of members returned

Name: ZRANGE
Summary: Returns members in a sorted set within a range of indexes.
Complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements returned.

Name: ZRANGEBYLEX
Summary: Returns members in a sorted set within a lexicographical range.
Complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

Name: ZRANGEBYSCORE
Summary: Returns members in a sorted set within a range of scores.
Complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

Name: ZRANGESTORE
Summary: Stores a range of members from sorted set in a key.
Complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements stored into the destination key.

Name: ZRANK
Summary: Returns the index of a member in a sorted set ordered by ascending scores.
Complexity: O(log(N))

Name: ZREM
Summary: Removes one or more members from a sorted set. Deletes the sorted set if all members were removed.
Complexity: O(M*log(N)) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements to be removed.

Name: ZREMRANGEBYLEX
Summary: Removes members in a sorted set within a lexicographical range. Deletes the sorted set if all members were removed.
Complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.

Name: ZREMRANGEBYRANK
Summary: Removes members in a sorted set within a range of indexes. Deletes the sorted set if all members were removed.
Complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.

Name: ZREMRANGEBYSCORE
Summary: Removes members in a sorted set within a range of scores. Deletes the sorted set if all members were removed.
Complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements removed by the operation.

Name: ZREVRANGE
Summary: Returns members in a sorted set within a range of indexes in reverse order.
Complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements returned.

Name: ZREVRANGEBYLEX
Summary: Returns members in a sorted set within a lexicographical range in reverse order.
Complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

Name: ZREVRANGEBYSCORE
Summary: Returns members in a sorted set within a range of scores in reverse order.
Complexity: O(log(N)+M) with N being the number of elements in the sorted set and M the number of elements being returned. If M is constant (e.g. always asking for the first 10 elements with LIMIT), you can consider it O(log(N)).

Name: ZREVRANK
Summary: Returns the index of a member in a sorted set ordered by descending scores.
Complexity: O(log(N))

Name: ZSCAN
Summary: Iterates over members and scores of a sorted set.
Complexity: O(1) for every call. O(N) for a complete iteration, including enough command calls for the cursor to return back to 0. N is the number of elements inside the collection.

Name: ZSCORE
Summary: Returns the score of a member in a sorted set.

Name: ZTTL
Summary: Returns the TTL in seconds of a sorted set member.
Complexity: O(N) where N is the number of specified members

Name: ZUNION
Summary: Returns the union of multiple sorted sets.
Complexity: O(N)+O(M*log(M)) with N being the sum of the sizes of the input sorted sets, and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.

Name: ZUNIONSTORE
Summary: Stores the union of multiple sorted sets in a key.
Complexity: O(N)+O(M log(M)) with N being the sum of the sizes of the input sorted sets, and M being the number of elements in the resulting sorted set.
